<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-632-219  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 632 219.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Engineering Times  Nov 19 1990 n617 p50(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Better procedures can boost EDA success. (electronic designautomation) (first of two parts)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Baker, Darrel.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Electronics manufacturers are scrambling to improve quality whilereducing design cycles and cost.andP;  Some companies are utilizingdesign automation, but not all are meeting with success.andP;  Oldprocedures and inefficient organization often prevent achievingdesign automation's maximum benefits.andP;  Using outdated procedureswith modern EDA tools produces inefficiencies that hamper designautomation.andP;  Tips on improving procedures include simplifyingdesign flow, integrating design data, exploiting analysis tools,managing the data, and enhancing management awareness andcommitment.andP;  Procedural improvements should follow a three-pointprogram: understand the current product-development process;develop a vision for design automation; and create transitionplans for implementing design automation.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     ManufacturersElectronic IndustryElectronic Design AutomationProduction ControlPerformance ImprovementQuality ControlCostOrganization Structure.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>